---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Production" active="production">
  <div class="container">

    <section class="page-header">
      <h3>Workflow</h3>
      <h1>Production</h1>
      <p>Build songs layer by layer. Logic records and provides the backing band. The Wing routes everything. The Model 12 mixes it all with real faders.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="vu-bar" style="background: rgba(90,138,74,0.35)"></div>

    <section class="ruled">
      <h3>Arranging with Band-in-a-Box</h3>
      <div class="prose mt-sm">
        <p>
          Songs start in Band-in-a-Box. Enter a chord progression, pick a style, set the tempo &mdash; and it generates a full arrangement: bass, drums, piano, guitar, strings, horns, whatever the style calls for. Hundreds of styles from jazz to country to rock, each with musically intelligent voicings and variations that respond to the chords.
        </p>
        <p>
          Once the arrangement feels right, export individual tracks as MIDI or audio into Logic. Use them as-is, layer them with Logic's session players, or replace parts with live performances as the song develops. Band-in-a-Box is the songwriter's sketchpad &mdash; the place where a chord chart becomes a full arrangement before a single note is recorded.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="ruled">
      <h3>Session Players</h3>
      <div class="prose mt-sm">
        <p>
          Logic Pro provides AI session players for bass, piano, synth, and drums. They play back through the Wing alongside live instruments &mdash; routed through the Wing and heard through the same monitoring path as everything else. During mixing, they flow through dedicated matrix buses to the Model 12 so each instrument gets its own fader and analog EQ.
        </p>
        <p>
          Between Band-in-a-Box arrangements and Logic's session players, a full backing band is always available. BIAB handles the initial arrangement and style exploration. Logic's players handle the backing parts during tracking &mdash; they play back generated parts that match the chord progression and tempo. Both feed into the same Wing channels and monitoring path.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="ruled">
      <h3>How a Track Gets Built</h3>
      <div class="grid-2 mt-sm">
        <div class="card">
          <span class="card__label">Step 1</span>
          <h4>Lay Down the Foundation</h4>
          <p>Record vocals and guitar through the outboard chain. Logic captures the processed signal. Session players provide the rhythm section live in the headphones.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="card__label">Step 2</span>
          <h4>Overdub</h4>
          <p>Previous takes play back through dedicated return channels with per-track effects &mdash; reverb, amp sims, whatever the part needs. New takes record simultaneously. No mode switching.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="card__label">Step 3</span>
          <h4>Shape the Arrangement</h4>
          <p>Adjust session player parts. Re-record sections. Try different amp sim tones on the guitar returns. The arrangement is fluid until you're ready to commit.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="card__label">Step 4</span>
          <h4>Mix on the Model 12</h4>
          <p>All tracks flow through Wing matrices to the Model 12. Set levels with real faders, shape tone with analog EQ, dial in tape saturation. Every pass is captured.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="ruled">
      <h3>Guitar Modes</h3>
      <div class="prose mt-sm">
        <p>
          The guitar DI feeds two amp sim buses before hitting the outboard chain. Switching between ANGEL (high-gain lead), DELUXE (clean rhythm), RACKAMP (acoustic), or a completely clean bypass is instant &mdash; just mute one bus and unmute another. The outboard chain stays the same regardless of which amp sim is active.
        </p>
        <p>
          During playback, recorded guitar tracks can be re-amped through the same chain. Solo the track, route it through an amp sim bus, and the outboard processes it again. The re-amped result records to a new track, giving you a completely different take on the same performance.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="ruled">
      <h3>Transport Sync</h3>
      <div class="prose mt-sm">
        <p>
          The Model 12 is the transport master. Press play on the Model 12 and Logic follows via MIDI timecode. This keeps the Model 12 in control of the timeline &mdash; it's the tape machine, and Logic provides the backing band. One button starts everything.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

  </div>
</Base>
